We decided to reduce the number of epochs from 200 to 15 for our Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) architectures. This is due to resource usage and hardware constraints. Training an RNN on a large dataset can be computationally expensive and can take a significant amount of time. Therefore, decreasing the number of epochs can significantly reduce the computational cost and runtime, making it possible to run the models within a reasonable timeframe.

In this case, reducing the number of epochs from 200 to 15 significantly improves the runtime from approximately 60 minutes to 5 minutes per epoch. The reduction in the training and testing data to 2000 records each also contributes to the decrease in runtime. While reducing the number of epochs may impact the accuracy and convergence of the model, the goal of the project is to demonstrate the implementation of RNNs, and 15 epochs is sufficient to showcase the architecture and functionality.

Therefore, reducing the number of epochs from 200 to 15 is a reasonable decision that balances computational cost and runtime with the project's objective.

Length of sequence¶

We decided to set a maximum of 1000 words per review in order to work within our hardware and time constraints. Given that running our RNN models take a considerable amount of time to run, we decided that 1000 words would be a good balance between running our models at a reasonable time and our models training efficiently with enough words per review.

Size and Nature of Vocabulary¶

We use a vocabulary text file that contains around 235,000 words. Given that a movie review could be written by anyone, we must consider different writing and word use styles. Therefore, we believe that using the entire vocabulary file for our tokenizer makes it less likely for our model to come across a English word it will not recognize and easier for our models to recognize the sentiment behind a combination of words, therefore preventing our models from becoming hindered in this aspect.

Dataset Source¶

This dataset was created as part of a research experiment and publication. The authors of the research paper and dataset only included highly polarizing movie reviews, meaning that all positive reviews were a 7 or more out of 10, and negative reviews were a 4 or lower out of 10. Additionally, each unique movie mentioned in the reviews of the dataset has at most 30 reviews each.

Additonal information on the dataset can be found here and more information on the research itself as well as the research paper published.

Evalutation Methods¶

✅ Choose and explain what metric(s) you will use to evaluate your algorithm’s performance. You should give a detailed argument for why this (these) metric(s) are appropriate on your data.
That is, why is the metric appropriate for the task (e.g., in terms of the business case for the task). Please note: rarely is accuracy the best evaluation metric to use. Think deeply about an appropriate measure of performance.

We will evaluate our models using different evaluation methods:

Accuracy is a measure of the overall correctness of a model's predictions, calculated as the ratio of the number of correct predictions to the total number of predictions. Accuracy provides us with a basic understanding of how our models are performing. It will not be our only evaluation method since accuracy only provides surface-level information and does not consider the full impact of false positives and negatives.

Misclass, or misclassification, refers to the instances where a model's prediction does not match the actual class label of a data point.

Precision is a measure of how well a model correctly identifies positive instances among the predicted positive instances. Given the nature of our dataset, we want to account for whether our model predicted a review to be negative when it was acutally positive (false positive) as movie reviews can influence the reputation of the movie.

Recall, also known as sensitivity or the true positive rate, is a measure of how well a model identifies all the positive instances among the actual positive instances. Given the nature of our dataset, we want to account for whether our model predicted a review to be positive when it was acutally negative (false negative) as movie reviews can influence the reputation of the movie.

F1-score is the "harmonic mean" of precision and recall, providing a single value that balances the trade-off between precision and recall.

Additionally, we graph the values of Loss and AUC (Area Under Curve) for comparisons.

We want to consider all of these metrics since not only do we want our models to perform well, but we want to achieve the highest true positive rate for both classes as possible. Given the importance of recognizing false positive and negatives, especially false negative reviews can have a greater impact on a movie's reputation than false positives, we need to measure and quantify the performance of our models by these evaluation methods.

Data Splitting Method¶

✅ Choose the method you will use for dividing your data into training and testing (i.e., are you using Stratified 10-fold cross validation? Shuffle splits? Why?).
Explain why your chosen method is appropriate or use more than one method as appropriate. Convince me that your train/test splitting method is a realistic mirroring of how an algorithm would be used in practice.

We chose to split our dataset using the train_test_split() function from the the sklearn.model_selection library. Our training and testing dataset contains around 2,000 observations each in order to run our models in a reasonable amount of time. Assuming that our dataset was only composed on 4,000 observations, the split would be 50/50 for training and testing. Since we used the stratify parameter in the train_test_split() function and passed in our target value, we ensure that the class distribution of this sub-dataset will be balanced like the overall dataset.

Our main motivation to shorten our dataset is due to resource usage and hardware constraints. Training an RNN on a large dataset can be computationally expensive and can take a significant amount of time.
Therefore, by decreasing the number of observations, it is possible to run the models within a reasonable timeframe.

While reducing the number of observations may impact the accuracy and convergence of the model, the goal of the project is to demonstrate the implementation of RNNs, and 4,000 observations total is still sufficient to showcase the architecture and functionality.

The code below splits the data into training and testing sets using the train_test_split() function from the scikit-learn library. The X and y_ohe variables contain the independent and dependent variables, respectively. The train_size and test_size parameters specify the number of observations in the training and testing sets, respectively. The stratify parameter is used to ensure that the distribution of the target variable (sentiment) is roughly equal in the training and testing sets.

This is important to ensure that the models trained on the data generalize well to new, unseen data to prevent the models from overfitting. GloVe Embedding¶

✅ Use the Glove pre-trained embedding. Provide justification of the embedding size.

We feel that 50 is a reasonable size for EMBED_SIZE. The size of the word embedding depends on the size of the corpus, the number of unique words, and the context window used to generate the embeddings.
In general, a larger embedding size tends to capture more complex semantic relationships between words, but this also requires more memory and computational resources.
Whereas smaller sizes may be suitable for smaller datasets or limited computing resources.
We observed that an embedding size of 50 strikes a balance in capturing relationships between words while also not draining our limited resources and taking an excess amount of time.

The code below loads pre-trained GloVe embeddings to use as initial weights for the model. The GloVe embeddings are stored in a text file, and the code reads the file into memory and parses the contents to obtain the embeddings for individual words. The embeddings are then stored in a dictionary, where each word is associated with a corresponding embedding vector. The size of each embedding vector is defined by the EMBED_SIZE constant.

Next, the code initializes an empty embedding matrix, which will be used to store the embeddings for the words in the training set. The matrix has dimensions (num_words, EMBED_SIZE), where num_words is the total number of unique words in the training set.

For each word in the word_index dictionary (which maps words to integer indices), the code checks if an embedding vector exists in the embeddings_index dictionary for that word. If an embedding vector exists, it is added to the embedding matrix at the corresponding index. If an embedding vector does not exist (i.e., the word is not in the pre-trained GloVe embeddings), the corresponding row in the embedding matrix remains all zeros.

Finally, the code prints the total number of word vectors found in the GloVe embeddings, as well as the number of words in the training set for which embeddings were found.

The review_test() helper function defined below tests a single review on a trained model to get the prediction. The function takes the trained model, the index of the review to be tested, and the test dataframe as arguments. The function then extracts the text and true label from the test dataframe using the provided index, displays the text and true label, and vectorizes the text using a pre-fitted tokenizer instance. The function then pads the text to have the same shape as the input to the embedding layer, feeds it to the model, and gets the predicted sentiment by performing an argmax operation on the model's output. Finally, the function displays the predicted sentiment.

In [ ]:
def review_test(model, index, test_df):
    """
    Tests a body of text on the trained model to get the prediction.
    """
    text = test_df["review"][index]
    display(HTML(f"<h5><b style='color:red'>Text: </b>{text}</h5>"))

    true_label = test_df["sentiment"][index]
    true_val = "negative" if true_label == 0 else "positive"
    display(HTML(f"<h5><b style='color:red'>Actual: </b>{true_val}</h5>"))

    # vectorizing the text by the pre-fitted tokenizer instance
    text = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(text)

    # padding the text to have exactly the same shape as `embedding` input
    text = pad_sequences(text, maxlen=MAX_ART_LEN, dtype="int32", value=0)

    sentiment = np.argmax(
        model.predict(text, batch_size=512, verbose=2)[0], axis=0
    )
    pred_val = "negative" if sentiment == 0 else "positive"
    display(HTML(f"<h5><b style='color:red'>Predicted: </b>{pred_val}</h5>"))

The helper function below creates a confusion matrix plot for a given sklearn confusion matrix, with several optional parameters. The function takes in a confusion matrix, the names of the classification classes, a title, a colormap, and a boolean to specify whether to plot the raw numbers or proportions. If normalize is True, the proportions are shown. The plot includes a color bar and the true and predicted labels as x and y-axis labels. The accuracy and misclassification rates are also displayed in the plot. The function also allows an optional argument class_results, which is a dictionary containing class-specific metrics to display.

In [ ]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(
    cm,
    target_names,
    title="Confusion matrix",
    cmap=None,
    normalize=True,
    class_results: dict = {},
):
    """
    Given a sklearn confusion matrix (cm), make a nice plot

    Arguments
    ---------
    cm:           confusion matrix from sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix

    target_names: given classification classes such as [0, 1, 2]
                  the class names, for example: ['high', 'medium', 'low']

    title:        the text to display at the top of the matrix

    cmap:         the gradient of the values displayed from matplotlib.pyplot.cm
                  see http://matplotlib.org/examples/color/colormaps_reference.html
                  plt.get_cmap('jet') or plt.cm.Blues

    normalize:    If False, plot the raw numbers
                  If True, plot the proportions

    Usage
    -----
    plot_confusion_matrix(cm           = cm,                  # confusion matrix created by
                                                              # sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix
                          normalize    = True,                # show proportions
                          target_names = y_labels_vals,       # list of names of the classes
                          title        = best_estimator_name) # title of graph

    Citiation
    ---------
    http://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_confusion_matrix.html

    """
    accuracy = np.trace(cm) / float(np.sum(cm))
    misclass = 1 - accuracy

    if cmap is None:
        cmap = plt.get_cmap("Blues")

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation="nearest", cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()

    if target_names is not None:
        tick_marks = np.arange(len(target_names))
        plt.xticks(tick_marks, target_names, rotation=45)
        plt.yticks(tick_marks, target_names)

    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype("float") / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

    thresh = cm.max() / 1.5 if normalize else cm.max() / 2
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        if normalize:
            plt.text(
                j,
                i,
                "{:0.4f}".format(cm[i, j]),
                horizontalalignment="center",
                color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black",
            )
        else:
            plt.text(
                j,
                i,
                "{:,}".format(cm[i, j]),
                horizontalalignment="center",
                color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black",
            )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    if class_results:
        x_lab = "Predicted label\n\n"
        x_lab += f"accuracy={accuracy:0.4f}\nmisclass={misclass:0.4f}\n"
        for key, value in class_results.items():
            x_lab += f"{key}={value:0.4f}\n"
    else:
        x_lab = "Predicted label\n\n"
        x_lab += f"accuracy={accuracy:0.4f}\nmisclass={misclass:0.4f}\n"
        
    plt.xlabel(x_lab)
    plt.show()

In this run, RNN1 predicted 751 Negative sentiments and 769 Positive sentiments correctly, while mispredicting 245 and 235 Negative and Positive sentiments respectively. The model does not show any bias towards any class in the images that it misclassified since the distribution of false positives and false negatives is balanced.

Accuracy is a measure of the overall correctness of a model's predictions, calculated as the ratio of the number of correct predictions to the total number of predictions. For this run, our initial accuracy score is 0.76 or roughly 76%.

Misclass, or misclassification, refers to the instances where a model's prediction does not match the actual class label of a data point. Misclassification can be measured using various metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score - but in this case we can easily determine misclass by calculating 1.0 minus the accuracy score. In our case, we observe the misclass as 0.24 or 24%.

Precision is a measure of how well a model correctly identifies positive instances among the predicted positive instances. Precision is calculated as the ratio of the number of true positive predictions to the total number of positive predictions (which would be the true positive predictions plus the false positive predictions). In our case, the precision score is 0.76 or 76%. It is the same as our accuracy value which we feel is ideal for finding a viable solution for field-use as it is important to minimize false positives and maximize true positives.

Recall, also known as sensitivity or the true positive rate, is a measure of how well a model identifies all the positive instances among the actual positive instances. Recall is calculated as the ratio of the number of true positive predictions to the total number of actual positive instances (i.e., sum of true positive and false negative predictions). Our recall score for this run was 0.76 or 76% - exactly the same as our accuracy.

F1-score is the "harmonic mean" of precision and recall, providing a single value that balances the trade-off between precision and recall. It is calculated as 2 (precision recall) / (precision + recall). Our F1-score for this run was 0.76 or roughly 76%.

In this run, RNN2 predicted 724 Negative sentiments and 607 Positive sentiments correctly, while mispredicting 272 and 397 Negative and Positive sentiments respectively. The model does show some bias towards class 1 as it misclassified more Negative reviews as Positive, and the margin between false positives and negatives is large.

Accuracy is a measure of the overall correctness of a model's predictions, calculated as the ratio of the number of correct predictions to the total number of predictions. For this run, our initial accuracy score is 0.66 or roughly 66%.

Misclass, or misclassification, refers to the instances where a model's prediction does not match the actual class label of a data point. Misclassification can be measured using various metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score - but in this case we can easily determine misclass by calculating 1.0 minus the accuracy score. In our case, we observe the misclass as 0.33 or 33%.

Precision is a measure of how well a model correctly identifies positive instances among the predicted positive instances. Precision is calculated as the ratio of the number of true positive predictions to the total number of positive predictions (which would be the true positive predictions plus the false positive predictions). In our case, the precision score is 0.66 or 66%. It is the same as our accuracy value which we feel is ideal for finding a viable solution for field-use as it is important to minimize false positives and maximize true positives.

Recall, also known as sensitivity or the true positive rate, is a measure of how well a model identifies all the positive instances among the actual positive instances. Recall is calculated as the ratio of the number of true positive predictions to the total number of actual positive instances (i.e., sum of true positive and false negative predictions). Our recall score for this run was 0.65 or 65% - just below our accuracy score.

F1-score is the "harmonic mean" of precision and recall, providing a single value that balances the trade-off between precision and recall. It is calculated as 2 (precision recall) / (precision + recall). Our F1-score for this run was 0.66 or roughly 66%.

RNN 3¶

The given code is a Keras model for a Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) with an Embedding layer, a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) layer, and a Dense layer. The model is compiled with the Adamax optimizer, mean squared error (MSE) loss, and uses two metrics: Recall and AUC. The model is then trained on training data X_train and y_train_ohe for 15 epochs and a batch size of 512, and validated using the testing data X_test and y_test_ohe. The summary of the model is displayed using the summary() function of the model.

Some differences between RNN3 and RNN1 is that the LSTM output size of RNN3 is 200 instead of 100, the dropout value of RNN3 is 0.25 instead of 0.3, and the recurrent dropout value of RNN3 is 0.25 instead of 0.3.

The dropout parameter of the LSTM layer states a fraction of the units that will be dropped for the linear transformation of the inputs. By changing the value from 0.3 to 0.25, we will include more units for the linear transformation of the inputs, which could have some impact in how the model reads in the inputs and its peformance on the testing dataset.

The recurrent_dropout parameter of the LSTM layer states a fraction of the units that will be dropped for the linear transformation of the recurrent state. By changing the value from 0.3 to 0.25, we will include more units for the linear transformation of recurrent state, which could have some impact on its peformance with the testing dataset.

The output shows a summary of the RNN model with its layers and the number of parameters in each layer. The model has a total of 1,906,452 parameters, out of which 201,202 are trainable, and the remaining 1,705,250 are non-trainable because they belong to the Embedding layer. The model has an Embedding layer that takes input of shape (None, 1000) and outputs a tensor of shape (None, 1000, 50), indicating that the input has 1000 words, and each word is represented by a 50-dimensional vector. The LSTM layer takes the output of the Embedding layer as input and produces a tensor of shape (None, 200) as output. Finally, the Dense layer produces a tensor of shape (None, 2) as output, representing the probabilities of the two classes in the binary classification problem.

Adding a Second Recurrent Chain¶

✅ Using the best parameters and architecture from the RNN in the previous step, add a second recurrent chain to your RNN. The input to the second chain should be the output sequence of the first chain. Visualize the performance of training and validation sets versus the training iterations.

Since RNN1 and RNN3 were our best performing models, and the models were implemented with an LSTM architecture, our RNN5 model with also be implemented with the same architecture, and we will use the parameters of RNN3 for RNN5.

The given code is a Keras model for a Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) with an Embedding layer, a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) layer, and a Dense layer. The model is compiled with the Adamax optimizer, mean squared error (MSE) loss, and uses two metrics: Recall and AUC. The model is then trained on training data X_train and y_train_ohe for 15 epochs and a batch size of 256, and validated using the testing data X_test and y_test_ohe. The summary of the model is displayed using the summary() function of the model.

Some differences between RNN5 the other LSTM RNN models (RNN1 and RNN3) is that the first LSTM layer output size of RNN3 is 200 instead of 100, following with an additional LSTM layer with an output size of 100. The dropout and recurrent_dropout value of RNN3 is 0.25, just like RNN3. The batch size is reduced from 512 (all four RNN models have this) to 256.

The dropout parameter of the LSTM layer states a fraction of the units that will be dropped for the linear transformation of the inputs. By changing the value from 0.3 to 0.25, we will include more units for the linear transformation of the inputs, which could have some impact in how the model reads in the inputs and its peformance on the testing dataset.

The recurrent_dropout parameter of the LSTM layer states a fraction of the units that will be dropped for the linear transformation of the recurrent state. By changing the value from 0.3 to 0.25, we will include more units for the linear transformation of recurrent state, which could have some impact on its peformance with the testing dataset.

The batch size of can greatly affect the performance of a model. In reducing the batch size by half, the model is less likely to be stuck in local minima and find the global minima, ultimately increasing the performance of the model.

The output shows a summary of the RNN model with its layers and the number of parameters in each layer. The model has a total of 2,026,652 parameters, out of which 351,402 are trainable, and the remaining 1,705,250 are non-trainable because they belong to the Embedding layer. The model has an Embedding layer that takes input of shape (None, 1000) and outputs a tensor of shape (None, 1000, 50), indicating that the input has 1000 words, and each word is represented by a 50-dimensional vector. The first LSTM layer takes the output of the Embedding layer as input and produces a tensor of shape (None, 200) as output. The second LSTM layer takes the output of the first LSTM layer as input and produces a tensor of shape (None, 100). Finally, the Dense layer produces a tensor of shape (None, 2) as output, representing the probabilities of the two classes in the binary classification problem.

The code section below defines the size of embedding and loads a pre-trained embedding file named 'numberbatch-en-17.04b.txt'. Then, it reads the text file into memory and assigns the glove data to a dictionary named 'embeddings_index', where the keys are the words and the values are the corresponding vectors. The code then prints the number of word vectors in the embedding file.

Next, the code initializes an embedding matrix of shape (len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE) with zeros. The variable 'found_words' counts the number of words that were found in the pre-trained embedding file. The code loops through each word in the 'word_index' and assigns its corresponding vector from 'embeddings_index' to the 'embedding_matrix'. If the word is not found in the 'embeddings_index', it is assigned an all-zeros vector.

Finally, the code prints the shape of the embedding matrix, the total words found, and the percentage of words found in the pre-trained embedding file.

In [ ]:
# Assigning embedding index
embeddings_index = {}

# Assigns glove data to embeddings dictionary.
for i, line in enumerate(glove_data):
    values = line.split()
    if values:
        word = values[0]
        coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype="float32")
        embeddings_index[word] = coefs

# Prints the number of word vectors.
print("Found %s word vectors." % len(embeddings_index))

# Fills in the matrix using the ordering from the keras
# word tokenizer that was implemented previously.
found_words = 0
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # words not found in embedding index will be ALL-ZEROS
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
        found_words = found_words + 1

The code below evaluates and visualizes the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve and Area Under the Curve (AUC) for RNNB. The ROC curve is a graphical representation of the performance of a binary classification system, showing the trade-off between the true positive rate (TPR) and the false positive rate (FPR) as the decision threshold for classification is varied. The AUC is a metric that summarizes the overall performance of the model, with a higher AUC indicating better performance.

Our AUC for this run is 0.84 indicating that the model has a good ability to distinguish between positive and negative cases. The ROC curve visualizes this by showing a rise in the curve until reaching a point where the TPR is 0.83 and the FPR is 0.17. From there, it gradually increases until reaching the end of the graph indicating that the model is able to identify some positive cases while making few false positive predictions. Overall, this suggests that the RNN model is able to make correct predictions will small room for improvement.

In this run, RNNB predicted 841 Negative sentiments and 841 Positive sentiments correctly, while mispredicting 155 and 163 Negative and Positive sentiments respectively. The model does not any bias towards any class 1, as the margin between the number of false positives and negatives is very small, similar to RNN1 and RNN5.

Accuracy is a measure of the overall correctness of a model's predictions, calculated as the ratio of the number of correct predictions to the total number of predictions. For this run, our initial accuracy score is 0.84 or roughly 84%.

Misclass, or misclassification, refers to the instances where a model's prediction does not match the actual class label of a data point. Misclassification can be measured using various metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score - but in this case we can easily determine misclass by calculating 1.0 minus the accuracy score. In our case, we observe the misclass as 0.15 or 15%.

Precision is a measure of how well a model correctly identifies positive instances among the predicted positive instances. Precision is calculated as the ratio of the number of true positive predictions to the total number of positive predictions (which would be the true positive predictions plus the false positive predictions). In our case, the precision score is 0.84 or 84%. It is the same as our accuracy value which we feel is ideal for finding a viable solution for field-use as it is important to minimize false positives and maximize true positives.

Recall, also known as sensitivity or the true positive rate, is a measure of how well a model identifies all the positive instances among the actual positive instances. Recall is calculated as the ratio of the number of true positive predictions to the total number of actual positive instances (i.e., sum of true positive and false negative predictions). Our recall score for this run was 0.83 or 83% - just below our accuracy score.

F1-score is the "harmonic mean" of precision and recall, providing a single value that balances the trade-off between precision and recall. It is calculated as 2 (precision recall) / (precision + recall). Our F1-score for this run was 0.83 or roughly 83%.
